NT|^B@2
Usually the opponent's club bid can be as short as three cards (sometimes even two!) and when the opponents have announced their fit in spades, it is more important to have a spade stopper than a club stopper. Given that partner has a pretty good hand, it is likely that partner will have a club stopper for us anyway.|
PG| ***** 188 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Overall we should trust partner's bidding more than the opponents'. Maybe your RHO has opened light, and maybe your LHO has responded light - whatever the case is, we should trust that partner has a good hand for his bidding. |
